- Error logs contain no raw error messages in the incident window and log.error_count is zero (often equal to p95, causing false-positive flags), so logs do not contradict metrics/traces.

Reasoning to localize root cause: 
- Per rules, when multiple faults exist across levels, select the level/component with the most significant deviation from its threshold (>>50%). MG02’s FIN-WAIT spike is the most extreme breach. 
- Traces show MG02 is a highly impacted downstream target receiving anomalous traffic from many sources at the same earliest timestamp. 
- The pattern (TCP FIN-WAIT spike on MG02 together with trace latency/row_count spikes and downstream disk/IO-wait increases) indicates connection churn/teardown at MG02 causing request processing/latency amplification across the call chain and triggering resource pressure on backend services.

Conclusion derived: MG02 is the most likely root cause component, with the root-cause occurrence at the start of the incident window (2021-03-09 21:00:00+08:00). The underlying reason is a network-level connection churn/teardown issue at MG02 (manifested as an extreme TCP FIN-WAIT spike) that caused increased request latency and cascading resource pressure (disk I/O and CPU IO-wait) across downstream services.
